Here's a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

#define WORD "hello"

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("text.txt");
    std::string line;
    int count = 0;

    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        std::string word = WORD;
        size_t pos = 0;
        while ((pos = line.find(word, pos))!= std::string::npos) {
            count++;
            pos += word.length();
        }
    }
    std::cout << "The word " << WORD << " occurred " << count << " times." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

In this program, we include the necessary headers for reading and manipulating strings. We define a constant WORD that specifies the word we want to count. Then, we declare a function main that opens the text file text.txt and reads each line using the std::getline function. 

In the while loop, we use the std::string::find function to find the position of the word in the current line. We specify the starting position as 0 in the first iteration, and then we update it to the next position in the following iterations. Once we find the word, we increment the count variable and repeat the process until we reach the end of the line.

Once we have read all the lines, we print the count of the specified word to the console. Finally, we return 0 to indicate a successful program execution.

